Why Getter & Setter?

Without them:

s1.age = -100;

Wrong.

With setter:

public void setAge(int age){

    if(age > 0){

        this.age = age;

    }

}

Now

s1.setAge(-100);

Nothing happens.

Your data stays safe.

This is the biggest advantage of Encapsulation.

Golden Formula
private

↓

Hide Data

↓

Setter

↓

Put Data Inside

↓

Getter

↓

Take Data Outside
One Small Program

Just read it.

class Student {

    private String name;

    public void setName(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }
}

Main

Student s1 = new Student();

s1.setName("Manohar");

System.out.println(s1.getName());

Output

Manohar
Super Easy Analogy 🏦

Think of a bank locker.

Locker = private

Deposit = Setter

Withdraw = Getter

You don't break open the locker.

You use the proper process.

Java works exactly the same way.

